revision.text:
{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2013}} {{Infobox World Series Expanded | image = <!-- none --> | country = World | year = 1904 | champion = [[1904 New York Giants season|New York Giants]] (NL) | champion_manager = [[John McGraw]] | champion_games = 106–47, .693, GA:&nbsp;13 | runnerup = [[1904 Boston Americans season|Boston Americans]] (AL) | runnerup_manager = [[Jimmy Collins]] | runnerup_games = 95–59, .617, GA:&nbsp;1.5 | date = N/A | MVP = <!-- none --> | television = <!-- none --> | announcers = <!-- none --> | radio_network = <!-- none --> | radio_announcers = <!-- none --> | umpires = N/A | HOFers = <!-- none --> | ALCS = <!-- none --> | NLCS = <!-- none --> | image2 = <!-- none --> }} In 1904, there was no [[World Series]] played between the champions of the two [[Major League Baseball|major leagues]], the [[American League]] (AL) and the [[National League]] (NL). The champions were the Boston Americans (now the [[Boston Red Sox]]), who repeated their 1903 AL championship, and the NL's New York Giants (now the [[San Francisco Giants]]).
==Background== [[File:America's National Game 0451.jpg|thumb|right|upright=0.6|New York Giants owner [[John T. Brush]]]] Due to a business rivalry between the two leagues, especially in New York, and to personal animosity between Giants manager [[John McGraw (baseball)|John McGraw]] and American League president [[Ban Johnson]], the Giants declined to meet the champions of the "junior" (or "minor") league. McGraw said his Giants were already the world champions because they were the champions of the "only real major league".<ref>{{cite journal|last=Vass|first=George|date=January 1995|title=Baseball's Shrunken Seasons: What Might Have Been...|journal=[[Baseball Digest]]|publisher=Lakeside Publishing Co|volume=54|issue=1|page=39|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GSsDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA39#v=onepage&q=&f=false|accessdate=December 28, 2009}}{{dead link|date=November 2015}}</ref>
During [[spring training]] in March 1904, Giants owner [[John T. Brush]] said "there will never be a series" between the New York-based teams—his Giants of the National League and the American League's [[New York Highlanders]]—in response to a preseason offer from Highlanders co-owner [[Frank J. Farrell]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/25295341/brush_declines/ |title=Brush Declines |newspaper=[[The Boston Globe]] |page=8 |date=March 8, 1904 |accessdate=November 11, 2018 |via=newspapers.com}}</ref> In July 1904, as reported in ''[[Sporting Life (American newspaper)|Sporting Life]]'', Brush stated that his NL club would not play the AL club "if each wins the [[Pennant (sports)|pennant]] in its respective league", in contradiction of a preseason agreement for a championship series between the leagues.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/24735450/baseball_notes/ |title=Baseball Notes |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |page=8 |date=July 6, 1904 |accessdate=October 21, 2018 |via=newspapers.com}}</ref><ref name=Scrapbook/>{{rp|57}} At that point in the season, the Giants were comfortably on top of the NL standings, and the Highlanders (now the [[New York Yankees]]) were just {{frac|1|1|2}} games behind the [[Boston Americans]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.retrosheet.org/boxesetc/1904/07041904.htm |title=Standings At Close of Play of July 4, 1904 |website=[[Retrosheet]]}}</ref> The AL race went down to the wire, and the Highlanders temporarily took over first place on October 7 when they defeated Boston.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.retrosheet.org/boxesetc/1904/10071904.htm |title=Standings At Close of Play of October 7, 1904 |website=[[Retrosheet]]}}</ref> But the Americans won three of their four remaining games to clinch the AL pennant, and finished {{frac|1|1|2}} games ahead of the Highlanders (who lost three of their final four games) in the final standings of October 10.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.retrosheet.org/boxesetc/1904/10101904.htm |title=Standings At Close of Play of October 10, 1904 |website=[[Retrosheet]]}}</ref> The Giants, who had won the NL by a wide margin (13 games), stuck to and broadened their plan, refusing to play ''any'' AL club, either the champion Boston team or the crosstown New York team, in the proposed "exhibition" series (as they considered it).<ref name=Scrapbook>{{cite book |title=The Scrapbook History of Baseball |first=Jordan A. |last=Deutsch |publisher=Bobbs-Merrill |date=1975 |isbn=0672520281 |url=https://www.amazon.com/Scrapbook-history-baseball-Jordan-Deutsch/dp/0672520281/}}</ref>{{rp|58}}
==Summary==
===Boston Americans=== Boston had defeated National League champion [[Pittsburgh Pirates|Pittsburgh]] in the [[1903 World Series]], a contest arranged by the two champion clubs, not by the leagues themselves.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/24736863/worlds_series_on_again/ |title=World's Series On Again |newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]] |page=6 |date=September 26, 1903 |accessdate=October 22, 2018 |via=newspapers.com}}</ref>
===New York Giants=== {{refimprove|section|date=December 2010}} The Giants maintained that the rules for the World Series were haphazardly defined. In the 1903 series, as well as postseason series between the National League and the [[American Association (19th century)|American Association]] in the 1880s, the rules for a given season's "World's Championship Series" had been whatever the two participating clubs had agreed upon. The World Series was not a compulsory event and was not governed by an authoritative body, thus the Giants were free to refuse to participate in such an event.
Stung by criticism from fans and writers, Brush drafted rules that both leagues adopted in mid-February 1905.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://research.sabr.org/journals/files/SABR-Baseball_Research_Journal-31-Bevis.pdf |title=The Evolution of World Series Scheduling |first=Charlie |last=Bevis |journal=The Baseball Research Journal |volume=31 |pages=21–28 |date=2003 |accessdate=October 22, 2018 |via=[[Society for American Baseball Research|SABR]]}}</ref> The rules compelled the two winning clubs to participate and governed the annual determination of sites, dates, ticket prices and division of receipts. These new rules essentially made the World Series the premier annual [[Major League Baseball]] event.
==Aftermath== Boston slumped in 1905, while New York repeated its NL championship and won the [[1905 World Series]] against the [[Philadelphia Athletics]]. The two teams eventually met in the [[1912 World Series]] with the Red Sox winning in seven games. The Series has been played every year since except {{wsy|1994}}, when a 232-day players' [[1994–95 Major League Baseball strike|strike]] ended the season in mid-August.
==References== {{reflist|30em}}
==Further reading== * {{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1994-09-15/sports/sp-38854_1_world-series |title=BASEBALL '94: Going, Going...Gone |first=Chris |last=Dufresne |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=September 15, 1994 |accessdate=October 22, 2018 |quote=Ninety years ago, the World Series was not played because of a personality feud between the sport's power brokers.}} * {{cite book |title=The Year They Called Off the World Series: A True Story |first=Benton |last=Stark |publisher=[[Avery Publishing]] |date=1991 |isbn=089529480X |url=https://www.amazon.com/Year-They-Called-Off-World/dp/089529480X/}}
