{{Infobox cricket ground | ground = Old Field cricket ground | image = | caption = | location = [[Bray, Berkshire]] | home club = [[Berkshire county cricket teams|Berkshire]] | county club = | established = by 1775 | last used = 1794 }}
'''Old Field''' at [[Bray, Berkshire]] was a noted [[cricket]] ground in the late 18th century. It was used as the venue for four [[first-class cricket|first-class matches]] between 1792 and 1795 in addition to several minor matches.<ref name=SB>Haygarth, pp.157–158.</ref><ref name=FC>[https://web.archive.org/web/20121010153247/http://www.jl.sl.btinternet.co.uk/stampsite/cricket/histories/matches.html Classification of cricket matches from 1697 to 1825]</ref><ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/11/2372_f.html CricketArchive – first-class matches at Old Field, Bray]</ref><ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/11/2372_misc.html CricketArchive – other matches at Old Field, Bray]</ref>
Bray is near [[Maidenhead]] and the ground was the home venue of Maidenhead Cricket Club when it was founded in the second half of the 18th century. It was used for first-class matches by the [[Berkshire county cricket teams|Berkshire county team]] which was very strong at that time.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20121010153250/http://www.jl.sl.btinternet.co.uk/stampsite/cricket/ladstolords/1781.html#1785 From Lads to Lord's – 1785]. Retrieved on 25 July 2009.</ref>
The name of the venue is correctly rendered "Old Field, Bray"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/11/2372.html |publisher=CricketArchive |title=Old Field, Bray |accessdate=29 January 2012}}</ref> but the designation "Oldfield Bray" is given by ''Scores and Biographies'' (S&B) which also calls the Berkshire team "Oldfield" in one match.<ref name=SB/> ''CricketArchive'' explains that S&B and other sources use Oldfield Bray as if "Bray" were part of the name of the ground. It has been established that the ground was called Old Field and was located in the parish of Bray, which in the 18th century included the southern half of what became Maidenhead, where the Old Field Club was based. Maidenhead was created as a separate parish in 1894.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/0/162.html |publisher=CricketArchive |title=Berkshire v Marylebone Cricket Club 1792 |accessdate=29 January 2012}}</ref>
